    <h2>SECTION A: Attempt any TWO question.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Why is it necessary to analyze the simulation output. Explain different estimation method which are used in simulatiom output analysis.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Analysis of simulation output</strong> mean to mean to predict output performance of the system or to compare the performance of two or more system designs. Analysis of simulation output is needed for following :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Verifies that the simulation model faithfully captures behavior in the actual world.</li>
<li>To predict the system performance or compare performance of two or more system designs.</li>
<li>Making decisions: Assists in deriving inferences from the data, enabling well-informed choices to be made in light of the simulation&#8217;s outcomes.</li>
<li>Error Reduction: Helps minimize possible mistakes by detecting randomness or variability in the simulation data.</li>
<li>Performance evaluation helps with optimization by gauging the simulated system&#8217;s performance in different settings.</li>
<li>Randomness and variability are common features of simulation outcomes and by analyzing these findings, it is feasible to evaluate the risk and dependability of different outcomes by quantifying the prediction uncertainty.</li>
</ul>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Point Estimation</strong></span> :</p>
<p>Point estimation is the process of estimating a single number, known as a &#8220;point estimate&#8221;, from sample data that represents the best estimate or guess of an unknown population parameter (e.g., variance, mean, or percentage). This one number is the parameter&#8217;s most likely value according to the information gathered. It uses sample data to generate a single best estimate or value for an unknown population parameter (such the mean, variance, or percentage). As an illustration, the sample mean.<br />
The population mean is served as a point estimate by <span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord accent"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="mord mathnormal">X</span><span class="accent-body"><span class="mord">ˉ</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose">)</span>. It’s called a “point” estimate because it gives a specific value, rather than a range.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Interval estimation</strong></span> :</p>
<p>With interval estimation, the unknown population parameter is predicted to fall within a range of values called a confidence interval. There is a certain likelihood that the interval contains the real value because it is computed with a particular confidence level (such as 95% or 99%).<br />
In contrast to point estimation, interval estimation takes sample variability into account and provides a range of reasonable values instead of a single estimate, increasing the inference&#8217;s dependability.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Consider that a machine tool in a manufacturing shop is turning out parts at the rate of two every 5 minutes. As they are finished, the parts go to an inspector, who takes 5±2 minutes to examine each one and reject about 15% of the parts. Now develop a block diagram and write the code for simulating the above problem using GPSS, and also explain the function of each block used in the block diagram in detail.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-44111 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/gpss.drawio-1.png?resize=163%2C563&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="163" height="563"></p>
<p>SIMULATE</p>
<p>GENERATE 5, 0         ; Generate part every 5 minute</p>
<p>QUEUE 1                      ; Place the part in queue when needed</p>
<p>SEIZE 1                         ; Seize the facility when available</p>
<p>DEPART 1                    ; parts leaves the queue</p>
<p>ADVANCE 5, 2            ;Inspector inspects the parts (5±2 minutes)</p>
<p>RELEASE 1                  ; Release the facility when served</p>
<p>TRANSFER 0.15, ACC, REJ</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">ACC TERMINATE 1    ; Those parts which are accepted and then terminate<br />
REJ TERMINATE 1    ; Those parts which are rejected and then terminate</p>
<p>END</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain the independenceand uniformity property of random number. For the following sample of random numbers, perform test for independence using K-S test. <strong>(D<sub>0.05,10</sub> = 0.41)<br />
</strong></p>
<p>0.35, 0.77, 0.12, 0.33, 0.88, 0.45, 0.19, 0.25, 0.91, 0.54</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Independence :<br />
</strong>The term &#8220;independence&#8221; describes the absence of any association or correlation between consecutive random values in a series. The value or occurrence of one number in a perfect random sequence shouldn&#8217;t reveal anything about the value or occurrence of the subsequent number.</p>
<p><strong>Uniformity :<br />
</strong>Uniformity indicates that each number in the sequence has the same chance of being chosen. A uniformly distributed random sequence has the same chance of occurrence for all values.</p>
<p><strong>Numerical part</strong>:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Null Hypothesis (H<sub>0</sub>)</strong></span> : The given set of numbers are random.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Alternative Hypothesis (H<sub>1</sub>)</strong> </span>: The given set of numbers are not random.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Level of Significance</strong></span> : D<sub>0.05</sub> = 0.521</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Test Statistics</strong></span> :<br />
Arranging the given numvers in ascending order:</p>
<p>0.12, 0.19, 0.25, 0.33, 0.35, 0.45, 0.54, 0.77, 0.88, 0.91</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44166 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/KS.drawio.png?resize=375%2C450&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="375" height="450"></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">D<sup>+</sup> = max {i/N  &#8211;  R(i)} = 0.113</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">D<sup>&#8211;</sup> = max {R(i) &#8211;  i-1/N} = 0.333</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">D = max{ D<sup>+</sup> , D<sup>&#8211;</sup> } = 0.333</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Conclusion</strong></span> :<br />
As D &lt; D<sub>0.05 </sub> i.e 0.333 &lt; 0.521 so the Null hypothesis is accepted i.e the num.</p>
</div>
