<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;"><strong>Static Physical Model</strong></td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;"><strong>Dynamic Physical Model</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It depicts the structure of a system at a certain moment in time.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It depicts the way a system changes or acts throughout time.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It shows no movement or changes over time.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It displays modifications, exchanges, and reactions to inputs.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">used frequently for permanent layouts, plans, and designs.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It is utilized in simulations to examine real-world phenomena, like as temperature or traffic.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">As it is time-dependent data is not used, it is easier and faster to create.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">More intricate development is needed, such as rules or algorithms to mimic real-world situations.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It is frequently employed for visual representation, as in product design, technology, and architecture.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It is often used to forecast system reactions in disciplines including economics, physics, biology, and engineering.</td>
</tr>
