/span></span><sub><span class="mjx-sub"><span id="MJXc-Node-70" class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I">n </span></span></span></sub></span><span id="MJXc-Node-71" class="mjx-mo MJXc-space3">= </span><span id="MJXc-Node-72" class="mjx-msubsup MJXc-space3"><span class="mjx-base"><span id="MJXc-Node-73" class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I">i</span></span></span><sub><span class="mjx-sub"><span id="MJXc-Node-74" class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I">n</span></span></span></sub></span><span id="MJXc-Node-75" class="mjx-mo">)</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>Now we can write down the whole Markov chain as a matrix P:</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44114 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Screenshot-602.png?resize=217%2C137&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="217" height="137"></p>
<p>Example:</p>
<p>Weather Problem:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>raining today  ⇒ 40 % rain tomorrow</li>
</ul>
<p>⇒ 60 % no rain tomorrow</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>not raining today  ⇒ 20 % rain tomorrow</li>
</ul>
<p>⇒ 80 % no rain tomorrow</p>
<p>What will be the probability if today is not raining then not rain the day after tomorrow?</p>
<p><i>Markov chain diagram:</i></p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-10953 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/download-2.png?resize=334%2C145&#038;ssl=1" alt="- Hamro CSIT" width="334" height="145" /></p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-44115" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Screenshot-603.png?resize=204%2C153&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="204" height="153"></p>
<p>Thus, the probability of not being rainy the day after tomorrow is 0.76.</p>
<p><strong>Applcation areas of Markov chain:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Physics</strong>: Whenever probabilities are employed to describe unknown or unmodeled system features, Markovian systems are widely utilized in statistical mechanics and thermodynamics. Assuming that the dynamics are time-invariant, it is unnecessary to take into account any pertinent history that is not included in the state description.</li>
<li><strong>Queuing Theory</strong>: Queues are treated analytically using Markov chains as the foundation. Because of this, they are essential for maximizing the efficiency of telecommunication networks, where messages frequently have to contend for scarce resources like bandwidth. Markov chains in continuous time are used in many queuing models.</li>
<li><strong>Internet Applications</strong>: Google uses a Markov chain to determine a webpage&#8217;s page rank. It is the likelihood that the following stationary distribution will have page x.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain itetrative process of calibrating a simulation model.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Calibration is the itetrative process of compearing the model to the real system and make adjustment to the model by compearing again and again. This comparision of model to the reality is carried out through by variety of test.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44149 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Untitled-Diagram.drawio-1.png?resize=265%2C248&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="265" height="248"></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>An initial model is built on the basis of the real system.</li>
<li>The initial model is compared to the real system and the adjustments are made.</li>
<li>The new model is again revised by comparing it to real system and the second version of the model is formed.</li>
<li>This itetration takes again and again until the  system built is close to the real system.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Describe the process of model building, verification and validation in detail with example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Process of model building</strong> :</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-44151 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Untitled-Diagram-Page-2.drawio.png?resize=201%2C203&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="201" height="203"></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The first step in model building consist of observing the real system and the interaction among various component and collecting data on its behaviour.</li>
<li>Next step in model building is construction of a conceptual model a collection of assumptions of the components and the structure of the system plus hypothesis of the values of model inpput parameters.</li>
<li>The third step is translation of the operatikonal model into the computer recognizable form or computer model.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Verification</strong> :<br />
It is the process of confirming that the simulation has been carried out accurately in accordance with its parameters and design.Verification examines the simulation&#8217;s capabilities, methods, and structure in order to determine whether it was constructed correctly. The software or model&#8217;s functionality and lack of programming or implementation problems are evaluated.</p>
<p><strong>Validation</strong> :<br />
It is the process of determining if the simulation accurately depicts the real-world system it is meant to mimic. The outputs or behavior of the simulation are compared to observations, empirical data, or experimental outcomes from the real system.It guarantees that the simulation is as accurate as is necessary for the task for which it was designed.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Define traffic intensity and server utilization. Write down the Kendall’s notation for queuing system with example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Traffic Intensity</strong>:<br />
The ratio of arrival rate to service rate is used to determine how busy a system is. It displays the percentage of the system&#8217;s capacity that is being utilized. A common way to represent traffic intensity is using the symbol ρ, which quantifies the demand on a queuing system in relation to its capacity. Formula: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ρ = μ/λ.</span></span></p>
<p><strong>Server utilization</strong> :<br />
The percentage of time a server (or service facility) is actively involved in serving tasks as opposed to being idle is known as server utilization. Server usage in a single-server system is equal to the traffic intensity. It is determined by dividing the arrival rate by the product of the service rate and the number of servers in multi-server systems.</p>
<p><strong>Kendall’s Notation:</strong></p>
<p>Different notations are frequently used in the queuing system and are called Kendall Notations. Kendall Notation is the standard system used to describe and classify a queueing node. The Kendall Notation can be represented in the form A/B/C/N/K.</p>
<p>where A indicates arrival pattern, B indicates service pattern, C indicates the number of servers, D indicates queuing discipline, N indicates system capacity, and K indicates calling population.</p>
<p>The symbols used for the probability distribution for inter-arrival time,  and service time are, D for deterministic, M for exponential, and E<sub>k</sub> for Erlang distribution.</p>
<p>If parameters D, N &amp; K are not specified then, N = ∞ (infinity), K = ∞ (infinity), D = FIFO</p>
<p>Example:</p>
<p>M/D/2/FIFO/5/∞, queuing system having exponential arrival pattern, deterministic service time, 2 servers, FIFO queuing discipline, the capacity of 5 customers, and infinite population.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Define traffic intensity and server utilization. Write down the Kendall’s notation for queuing system with example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Traffic Intensity</strong>:<br />
The ratio of arrival rate to service rate is used to determine how busy a system is. It displays the percentage of the system&#8217;s capacity that is being utilized. A common way to represent traffic intensity is using the symbol ρ, which quantifies the demand on a queuing system in relation to its capacity. Formula: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ρ = μ/λ.</span></span></p>
<p><strong>Server utilization</strong> :<br />
The percentage of time a server (or service facility) is actively involved in serving tasks as opposed to being idle is known as server utilization. Server usage in a single-server system is equal to the traffic intensity. It is determined by dividing the arrival rate by the product of the service rate and the number of servers in multi-server systems.</p>
<p><strong>Kendall’s Notation:</strong></p>
<p>Different notations are frequently used in the queuing system and are called Kendall Notations. Kendall Notation is the standard system used to describe and classify a queueing node. The Kendall Notation can be represented in the form A/B/C/N/K.</p>
<p>where A indicates arrival pattern, B indicates service pattern, C indicates the number of servers, D indicates queuing discipline, N indicates system capacity, and K indicates calling population.</p>
<p>The symbols used for the probability distribution for inter-arrival time,  and service time are, D for deterministic, M for exponential, and E<sub>k</sub> for Erlang distribution.</p>
<p>If parameters D, N &amp; K are not specified then, N = ∞ (infinity), K = ∞ (infinity), D = FIFO</p>
<p>Example:</p>
<p>M/D/2/FIFO/5/∞, queuing system having exponential arrival pattern, deterministic service time, 2 servers, FIFO queuing discipline, the capacity of 5 customers, and infinite population.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>What is analog computer ? Explain with suitable example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>An analog computer is a kind of computing equipment that uses continuous impulses to represent data. These signals can include mechanical, hydraulic, or electronic components. Because they can analyze and modify continuous data, analog computers are ideal for jobs involving physical quantities and measurements.</p>
<p><strong>Characteristics of Analog Computers:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Continuous Signals</strong> : Continuous signals enable a smooth representation of values and are used by analog computers to represent data.</li>
<li><strong>Speed</strong> : For some jobs, analog computers may process information more quickly than digital computers.</li>
<li><strong>Accurate Measurement</strong> : Excellent for assignments involving actual measurements and phenomena.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Analog Computer Example</strong> :<br />
An analog electronic thermometer is an example of an analog computer. The continuous analog representation of temperature in this device is provided by the location of a mercury column in a glass tube.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes:</p>
<ol>
<li>Queuing discipline</li>
<li>Random variate</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Queue Discipline :<br />
</strong>A queuing discipline is the body of regulations that establishes the sequence in which work or clients are handled in a line.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">FIFO (First-In-First-Out)</span>: This queuing discipline tells that the entity that arrives first is the first to be served. eg: the one with first entry in the bank will get first served.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">LIFO (Last-In-First-Out)</span>: This queuing discipline tells that the entity that arrives last is the first to be served. for eg: thehistory of the browser, the last existed tab is displayed first in history.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Priority Queues</span>: A special way where the entities are served based on assigned priorities.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">(SIRO) Service in Random Order</span> : A queuing discipline where the service is given to any random. Here, no any algorithm is used to determine which process or customer would be the next.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">SPT (Shortest Process Time)</span> :  When the process or customer with the shortest time is given the first service then it is called SPT i.e Shortest Process Time.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Random variate :<br />
</strong>A value that is produced at random from a certain probability distribution is known as a random variate. In statistical modeling, simulations, and probabilistic analysis, it is used to simulate random processes in a controlled way by representing a potential result of a random variable.<br />
An exponential distribution is frequently used to describe the time between client arrivals in a queue. For example, each random variate produced from this distribution would represent one potential arrival time, according to the statistical characteristics of that distribution.</p>
</div>
